CURSOR RULES (GLOBAL SYSTEM PROMPT)

1. CORE PRINCIPLES
- Prioritise simplicity, clarity, and maintainability over cleverness
- Avoid overengineering and premature abstraction
- Prefer existing patterns in the codebase over introducing new ones
- Write code that is easy to read, test, and modify
- Optimise for long-term maintainability, not short-term elegance

2. EXECUTION WORKFLOW
When completing a task:
- Understand requirements and inspect existing code first
- If anything is unclear, ask clarifying questions
- Identify the smallest correct change to achieve the goal
- For non-trivial tasks, outline an approach before coding
- Implement incrementally (avoid large, monolithic changes)
- Validate changes against existing patterns and constraints

3. CHANGE SAFETY RULES
- Do not modify unrelated code
- Keep changes minimal and scoped
- Do not refactor unless explicitly required or directly improving the task area
- Do not rename APIs, functions, or files without necessity
- Preserve existing behaviour unless explicitly asked to change it
- Avoid full-file rewrites unless required

4. CODE QUALITY STANDARDS
- Code must be readable without requiring external explanation
- Use clear, descriptive naming
- Keep functions small and single-purpose
- Avoid deep nesting and overly complex logic
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Avoid unnecessary abstraction

5. ARCHITECTURE RULES
- Follow existing architecture patterns in the codebase
- Do not introduce new architectural patterns without justification
- Abstraction is only allowed when there are at least 2 clear use cases
- Keep modules feature-focused and self-contained
- Separate UI, business logic, and data access layers where applicable
- Prefer modular, decoupled design

6. STATE & DATA FLOW RULES
- Keep state management consistent across the project
- Avoid duplicated or conflicting sources of truth
- Prefer unidirectional data flow
- Isolate side effects in services or dedicated layers
- Keep UI components as stateless as practical

7. DEPENDENCY RULES
- Do not add new dependencies without justification
- Prefer built-in or native framework solutions first
- Only use well-maintained, widely adopted libraries
- Avoid duplicate libraries solving the same problem
- Do not introduce experimental dependencies without explicit need

8. ERROR HANDLING RULES
- Handle expected failures explicitly
- Never silently ignore errors
- Log errors with meaningful context
- Ensure graceful degradation in UI or API responses
- Prefer typed or structured error handling where possible

9. TESTING & RELIABILITY
- Write code with testability in mind
- Separate logic from UI to enable unit testing
- Add tests for bug fixes to prevent regression
- Prefer simple unit tests over complex test setups

10. PERFORMANCE RULES
- Do not optimise prematurely
- Prefer readability over micro-optimisations
- Only optimise when there is clear evidence or need
- Avoid unnecessary memoisation, caching, or complexity

11. TERMINAL RULES
- Always provide commands instead of executing them
- Explain what each command does before suggesting it
- Avoid destructive commands unless explicitly required
- Prefer safe, reversible operations

12. ANTI-PATTERNS
Never:
- Overengineer simple problems
- Introduce unnecessary abstractions
- Create large monolithic files or classes
- Mix UI, business logic, and data layers
- Modify unrelated code
- Remove or rewrite working logic without necessity

13. CONSISTENCY RULES
- Match existing code style and patterns
- Do not introduce new conventions unless migrating intentionally
- Keep naming, structure, and patterns consistent across modules
- Respect existing folder and feature boundaries

14. DOCUMENTATION & COMMENTS
- Do not remove existing comments unless code is removed
- Comments should explain WHY, not WHAT
- Keep comments minimal and meaningful
- Document non-obvious decisions only

15. KNOWLEDGE CAPTURE
If a solution required significant debugging or insight:

Add it to MyKnowledgeBase.txt in the project root

Format:
<Topic Title>
- Insight
- Root cause
- Lesson learned

16. FILE RESPONSIBILITY RULES
- Each file must have a single clear responsibility
- Split files when they grow beyond a focused concern
- Avoid utility dumping grounds
- Shared code must be genuinely reusable

17. FINAL RULE
Code should always be:
- easy to read
- easy to change
- safe to extend

If a solution feels complex → simplify it.